","Abt 1379":"omkring 1379","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1406":"1406","Luss, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Luss, Dunbartonshire, Skotland",",,, SCOT":"Skotland, United Kingdom","Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Houston, Renfrewshire, Skotland, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1360–":"1360–Overleden","1360–Female":"1360–Overleden","1367–Male":"1367–Overleden","1369–Male":"1369–Overleden","1372–Male":"1372–Overleden","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1397–1456":"1397–1456","1345–1397":"1345–1397","1341–Female":"1341–Overleden","ABT 1371":"circa 1371","1369":"1369","1456":"1456","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1397":"1397","1341":"1341","Abt 1379":"circa 1379","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1406":"1406","Luss, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Luss, Dunbartonshire, Schotland",",,, SCOT":"Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Houston, Renfrewshire, Schotland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1360–":"1360–Deceased","1360–Female":"1360–Deceased","1367–Male":"1367–Deceased","1369–Male":"1369–Deceased","1372–Male":"1372–Deceased","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1397–1456":"1397–1456","1345–1397":"1345–1397","1341–Female":"1341–Deceased","ABT 1371":"about 1371","1369":"1369","1456":"1456","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1397":"1397","1341":"1341","Abt 1379":"about 1379","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1360":"1360","1406":"1406","Luss, Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Luss, Dunbartonshire, Scotland",",,, SCOT":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fraser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: apparently a nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>fraser(e)</i>, <i>fresere</i> ‘strawberry plant’. <i>Fresel</i> and <i>Frisel</i>, from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, are early variants of the Fraser surname, the modern Gaelicized form of which is <b>Friseal</b>. See   Frizzell  . The crest on the Scottish family's coat of arms takes the form of a strawberry plant, but its antiquity is unknown. Claims of a habitational derivation, in particular from a place called la Frézelière in Anjou (France), are attractive but they lack verifiable evidence.","Americanized form of one or more similar (like-sounding) Jewish surnames.","History: There are two clans Fraser in Scotland, with common ancestry going back to Simon Fraser of Keith in East Lothian, who lived in the 12th century. One of these clans has its seat at Philorth Castle (subsequently re-named Cairnbulg) on the northeast coast of Scotland. Sir Alexander Fraser, 8th laird of Philorth (<i>c.</i> 1536–1623) converted the fishing village of Faithlie into the burgh of Fraserburgh in the 1590s. The other clan is Fraser of Lovat, associated mainly with the city of Inverness are. They are descended from Simon Fraser, a younger son, who lived in the early 14th century. In Gaelic, the head of Clan Fraser of Lovat is known as <i>Mac Shimi</i> ‘son of Simon’."],"variants":[{"name":"Frayser","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frasure","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazer","meanings":["Variant of   Fraser  , associated chiefly with northern Ireland."]},{"name":"Fraizer","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frashier","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Fraiser","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frizzell","meanings":["English and Irish: nickname from Old French <i>fresel</i>, <i>frisel</i> ‘lace, ribbon, braid, brooch, frill, ruff’, for someone with an ornate style of dress, or ‘object of little value’ (a diminutive of <i>frese</i>, of ancient Germanic origin).","Scottish: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fresel</i> ‘strawberry’, an alternative form of   Fraser  ."]},{"name":"Frazier","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Fraser  .","Americanized form of French <b>Frégeau</b> (see   Fregeau  )."]},{"name":"Frasher","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Fraser  .","Possibly an altered form of German <b>Fratzscher</b> (see   Frutchey  )."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Fraser was born in 1360, in Luss, Dunbartonshire, Scotland, her father, Sir John Fraser of Auchinschogill, was 16 and her mother, Mrs. Marjory Fraser of Monymusk, was 20. She married Humphrey Colquhoun 6th Colquhoun of that Ilk about 1379. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1360–":"1360–Surnud","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1367–